name: 3-[(4-nitrophenyl)hydrazono]-1,4-diphenylbutan-2-ol
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3347
Reason: To estimate the melting point of 3-[(4-nitrophenyl)hydrazono]-1,4-diphenylbutan-2-ol, several functional groups and structural features must be considered. Starting with a reference molecule, such as benzene (which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius), the following adjustments can be made: Each additional phenyl group adds to the melting point due to increased van der Waals interactions and symmetry; this can be estimated as +30 degrees Celsius per additional phenyl ring. The nitro group generally raises the melting point due to its strong electron-withdrawing nature, which may enhance intermolecular interactions; this could be around +40 degrees Celsius. The hydrazone moiety typically increases the melting point because it can participate in hydrogen bonding and has a planar structure, contributing to lattice stability; let's estimate this at +20 degrees Celsius. The butan-2-ol, while introducing some polarity and potential hydrogen bonding, adds less to the melting point than the previous groups due to the increased molecular weight and chain length; we'll estimate a +10 degree Celsius increase. Adding these increments to the base melting point of benzene gives a predicted melting point for the target compound.
Prediction: 5.5 (for benzene) + 30 (additional phenyl group) + 30 (second additional phenyl group) + 40 (nitro group) + 20 (hydrazone moiety) + 10 (butan-2-ol group) = 135.5 degrees Celsius
